\abstract{
The heterogeneity and high mobility of 5G Vehicular Edge Computing (VEC) networks create non-stationary environments where standard offloading algorithms often fail. A critical issue in decentralized multi-agent scenarios is the "Thundering Herd" phenomenon, where autonomous agents simultaneously target the same optimal resource, causing sudden congestion and performance collapse. This paper proposes a novel \textbf{Risk-Aware Fuzzy-Adaptive Independent Q-Learning (RA-FA-IQL)} approach. Unlike traditional methods, our solution dynamically tunes the learning rate ($\alpha$) and the exploration entropy (Softmax temperature) based on real-time Fuzzy inference of "Drift" and "Queue Risk". Simulation results demonstrate that RA-FA-IQL outperforms standard IQL and Sliding-Window UCB in critical stress scenarios (Arrival Rate $\approx$ 5.4), reducing average queue size by 25.6\% and latency by 14.5\% while maintaining a Jain's Fairness Index above 0.91.
}

\keywords{Task Offloading, Thundering Herd, Independent Q-Learning, Fuzzy Logic, Entropy Control, Non-Stationary V2X}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}\label{sec_introduction}

The convergence of 5G New Radio (NR) and Vehicular Edge Computing (VEC) enables ultra-low latency applications for autonomous driving. However, the decision of task offloading in a decentralized environment presents a classic Game Theoretic dilemma: the \textit{Thundering Herd} problem. When multiple vehicles independently learn that a specific Roadside Unit (RSU) provides the best service, they simultaneously migrate their workloads to it, causing immediate congestion and service degradation.



Existing solutions typically rely on centralized coordination or complex communication overheads to achieve load balancing. In contrast, Reinforcement Learning (RL) approaches, such as Independent Q-Learning (IQL), offer decentralized decision-making but suffer from instability in non-stationary environments where channel qualities drift and network load fluctuates rapidly.

To address these challenges, we propose a hybrid architecture: **Risk-Aware Fuzzy-Adaptive IQL (RA-FA-IQL)**. Our contribution is threefold:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item We model the VEC environment as a Non-Stationary Decentralized Partially Observable MDP (Dec-POMDP) with congestion effects.
    \item We introduce a Fuzzy Logic Controller that manipulates the \textit{Entropy} of the agent's policy. By dynamically adjusting the Softmax temperature, the agents spontaneously "spread out" during congestion events without explicit communication.
    \item We validate the model in a high-stress simulation, demonstrating survival capabilities where baseline algorithms fail.
\end{enumerate}

\section{System Model}\label{sec_system_model}

We consider a network with $N$ autonomous vehicles and $K$ RSUs. The system is modeled to reflect realistic non-stationary behaviors, including physical channel drift and load-dependent latency.

\subsection{Non-Stationary Environment}
The environment is characterized by a "Drift" process where the baseline latency of RSUs changes abruptly over time (simulating shadowing or handover). Additionally, the effective latency $L_{eff}$ of an RSU follows a congestion function:
\begin{equation}
    L_{eff} = L_{base} \times \gamma^{(n-1)}
\end{equation}
where $n$ is the number of concurrent users and $\gamma$ is the penalty factor. This nonlinearity creates the "trap" for greedy algorithms.

\section{Proposed Solution: RA-FA-IQL}\label{sec_methodology}

The core innovation is the integration of a Fuzzy Meta-Controller atop a standard Q-Learning agent. The agent does not use static hyperparameters; instead, its learning plasticity ($\alpha$) and exploration strategy ($\tau$) are functions of its internal state risk and external surprise.



\subsection{Fuzzy Logic Controller (FLC)}
The FLC takes two crisp inputs:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{TD-Error ($|\delta|$):} Represents the "Surprise" or Drift. A high error indicates the environment has changed.
    \item \textbf{Queue Usage ($Q_{pct}$):} Represents the "Risk". High usage indicates imminent buffer overflow.
\end{itemize}



The FLC outputs three control variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Learning Rate ($\alpha$):} Increases when Drift is detected to quickly adapt to new RSU qualities.
    \item \textbf{Temperature ($\tau$):} Controls the Entropy of the Softmax policy. High $\tau$ flattens the probability distribution, effectively forcing Load Balancing among agents.
    \item \textbf{Panic Mode ($P$):} A binary trigger. If $Q_{pct} > 0.6$ (Critical), the agent abandons exploration and reverts to a Greedy strategy to drain the queue.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Entropy-based Load Balancing}
Unlike $\epsilon$-greedy strategies, we utilize a dynamic Softmax policy:
\begin{equation}
    \pi(a|s) = \frac{e^{Q(s,a)/\tau}}{\sum_{k} e^{Q(s,k)/\tau}}
\end{equation}
When the FLC detects congestion (via high TD-error and moderate risk), it increases $\tau$. This mathematical manipulation causes the agents to probabilistically disperse across suboptimal RSUs, resolving the Thundering Herd problem organically.

\section{Experimental Evaluation}\label{sec_experiments}

We evaluated the proposed RA-FA-IQL against three baselines: \textit{Random}, \textit{Standard IQL}, and \textit{Sliding-Window UCB (SW-UCB)}.
The simulation was configured with an \textbf{Arrival Rate of 5.4 tasks/step}, a critical "Sweet Spot" calculated to exceed the capacity of a single RSU but fit within the capacity of a balanced system.

\subsection{Numerical Results}

Table \ref{tab:results} summarizes the performance metrics over 2000 simulation steps.

\begin{table}[h]
    \caption{Performance Comparison (Stress Scenario)}
    \label{tab:results}
    \centering
    \begin{tabular}{lcccc}
        \toprule
        \textbf{Algorithm} & \textbf{Avg Queue} & \textbf{Max Queue} & \textbf{Latency (s)} & \textbf{Fairness} \\
        \midrule
        Random       & 92.69 & 98.85 & 0.8798 & 0.8893 \\
        SW-UCB       & 73.22 & 90.19 & 0.5140 & 0.7748 \\
        Standard IQL & 42.81 & 56.91 & 0.5597 & 0.8874 \\
        \textbf{RA-FA-IQL} & \textbf{31.82} & \textbf{41.54} & \textbf{0.4782} & \textbf{0.9186} \\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Discussion}

\subsubsection{Survival Analysis (Queue Management)}
As shown in Table \ref{tab:results}, Random and SW-UCB agents failed to manage the queue, reaching near-saturation levels ($>90$ packets). Standard IQL managed to survive but operated with a high average queue of 42.81. The RA-FA-IQL reduced the average queue to 31.82 (a 25.6\% improvement), proving its superior risk management capability via the "Panic Mode" mechanism.

\subsubsection{Latency and Fairness}
Surprisingly, RA-FA-IQL achieved the lowest latency (0.478s), outperforming the "Greedy" Standard IQL. This counter-intuitive result confirms that in high-load regimes, \textit{cooperation} (via entropy-induced load balancing) yields faster processing than competition. The Jain's Fairness Index of 0.9186 confirms that RA-FA-IQL effectively utilizes all available RSUs, whereas SW-UCB (0.7748) suffered from severe load imbalance.

\section{Conclusion}\label{sec_conclusion}
This paper introduced RA-FA-IQL, a hybrid learning approach for VEC. By dynamically coupling Fuzzy Logic with Q-Learning, we demonstrated that manipulating policy entropy is a viable strategy to solve the Thundering Herd problem without inter-agent communication. Future work will explore the implementation of this logic on FPGA-based Smart NICs.

